{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"Included with: <b> πρᾶος</b>, ον, <br /> also <b>πρᾱΰς</b>, <i>Ionic dialect</i> <b>πρηΰς</b>, εῖα, ΰ:—<b>πρᾶος</b> supplies <i>singular</i> in <i>Attic dialect</i>, Trag., and Comedy texts, except that the <i>feminine</i> is always πραεια (πρᾶος as <i>feminine</i> only in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.168d)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; but <i>singular</i> <u><b>πραΰς</b></u>, <i>Ionic dialect</i> <b>πρηΰς</b>, is used in <i>Epic dialect</i> and Lyric poetry (also in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus and usually in LXX, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus, etc.)\">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>plural</i>, <i>nominative</i> πρηέες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιδημίαι” 1.10, πρηεῖς “Anthologia Graeca” 5.208 (3rd c.BC: Posidippus Comicus or 3rd c.BC: Asclepiades Epigrammaticus), πρᾶοι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 562d, etc.; _feminine_ πρηεῖαι “Anthologia Graeca” 6.244 (1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Crinagoras Epigrammaticus); _neuter_ πραέα 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 15.4, “Eq.” 9.10, etc., πρᾶα 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 488b22, _falsa lectio_ in 1st c.AD: Philo Judaeus 2.351; _genitive_ πραέων 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 1.4.9; _dative_ πραέσι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 888a, 930a, _feminine_ πραίαις\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] written for πραείαις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 7.3101 (Lebad., 3rd c.AD)\">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; <i>accusative</i> πραεῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 18.37.7, πράους 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 3.55 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>comparative</i> πραότερος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 20.21, πραΰτερος 5th c.BC: Epicharmus Comicus 153, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 85a, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>Ionic dialect</i> πρηΰτ- [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.181 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>superlative</i> πραότατος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 116c, etc., πραΰτατος “Syria” 5.337 (from Sidon)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> and <i>Ionic dialect</i> πρηΰτατος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 2.937, “Anthologia Graeca” 6.349 (1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus); πράϋστος “MAMA” 1.237 (from Phrygia)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]. (The ι subscr. is frequently written in codices, but Πρᾶος is written in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.1928.20 (_proper name_, 4th c.BC), “IGRom.” 4.504 (Pergam.), compare 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc., “Etymologicum Gudianum” 478.31\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; πραύτερος is found once in codices, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Ti.” [prev. cited] (proved wrong by πραΰς “Comica Adespota” in “Gött. Nachr.” 1922.31, πραέα (_neuter_ _plural_) in “PCair.Zen.” 33.12 (3rd c.BC), πραέως “UPZ” 144.6 (2nd c.BC), and by the absence of iota in _Ionic dialect_ πρηΰς))\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>mild, soft, gentle</b> (not in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” or 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey”): \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__1</b></Level3> of things, πρηῢ σέλας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “H.Hom.” 8.10; πραῢς ὄαρος 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.136 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>mild,</b> πυρετοί Hp.[same place]; ἰητρείη πρηεῖα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Art.” 69 \">Refs</a>]; of sound, <b>soft, gentle,</b> τὴν φωνὴν πραοτέραν ποιοῦνται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 1.10; ἀνέμων πρηΰτατε Ζέφυρε “Anthologia Graeca” 6.349 (1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὠδῖνες[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 244 (1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Crinagoras Epigrammaticus); κέντρον [prev. work] 229 ([prev. author]). \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of persons, <b>mild, gentle, meek,</b> πραῢς ἀστοῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 3.71; πᾶσιν ἵλεώς τε καὶ πρᾶος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 566e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς τοὺς οἰκείους π.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 375c; π. τὸ ἦθος [prev. author] “Phdr.” 243c; π. ἐν τοῖς λόγοις [prev. author] “Euthd.” 303d \">Refs</a>]; especially after having been angry, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.181 (_comparative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ θὴρ ὅδ᾽ ἡμῖν π., of Dionysus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 436 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a horse, <b>gentle,</b> ἀλλήλοις πραότεροι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.1.29 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of other animals, <b>tame,</b> ἰχθύων μεγάλων καὶ πραέων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “An.” 1.4.9, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 488b22; ζῷα.. πραέα πρὸς τοὺς ἀνθρώπους 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 15.4: proverbial, πραΰτερος μολόχας 5th c.BC: Epicharmus Comicus 153; also, τόπος ἡμερώτερος καὶ πραότερος 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 9.67. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of actions, feelings, etc., <b>mild,</b> τιμωρίαι πραότεραι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 867b; πραότεραι ἡδοναί [prev. work] 815e; λόγοι, ἤθη, φύσις, [prev. work] 888a, 930a, “R.” 375c; ὄσσοισι πρηέσιν δέρκευ “BMus.Inscription” 921b8 (Branchidae, 1st-2nd c.AD)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὰ πραέα <b>caresses,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 9.10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πραότερα πάσχειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Pl  “Cri.” 49b. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>making mild, taming,</b> φάρμακον πραῢ τείνων ἀμφὶ γένυι, of a bridle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.85; προκινεῖν αὐτὸν [τὸν ἵππον] ὡς πραοτάτοις σημείοις 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 9.3. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>adverb</i> <b>πράως</b>, <b>mildly, gently,</b> πράως πείθειν τινά, φέρειν τι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 589c, “Cri.” 43b; πράως ἔχειν πρός τι [prev. author] “Ly.” 211e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πράως λέγειν τὸ πάθος to speak <b>lightly</b> of it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 1.5.14 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πράως διακεῖσθαι, opposed to ὀργίζεσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.183; πράως, μὴ πικρῶς [prev. author] 18.265 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; in physical sense, <b>gently,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Oribasius Medicus “fragment” 134: _comparative_, πραότερον προδιδάσκειν, κολάζειν, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 489d, “Phd.” 94d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πραοτέρως (variant{-υτέρως}) ἔχειν τινί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 17.6.4 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: <i>superlative</i>, φέρειν.. ὡς πραότωτα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 387e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: later form <b>πραέως</b> (πράως [Ἀττικοί], οὐ πραέως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc.), “UPZ” 144.6 (2nd c.BC), 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 1.36, 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 1.13, uncertain in “Comica Adespota” 336.5 (compare πρατίας)\">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>], etc.: <i>Ionic dialect</i> <b>πρηέως</b> conjecture in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 46 (πράως and πραέως codices)\">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]. (Cogn. with Sanskrit <i>prīṇā´ti</i> 'love, give pleasure to', Gothic <i>frijon</i> 'love', <b>frijonds</b> 'friend'.)","strongNumber":"G4239","accentedUnicode":"πραΰς","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4239","matchingForm":"πραΰς","stepTransliteration":"praus","gloss":"gentle","_zh_tw_Gloss":"溫柔","_es_Gloss":"manso","_zh_Gloss":"温柔"},{"strongNumber":"G4240","matchingForm":"πραΰτης","stepTransliteration":"prautēs","gloss":"gentleness","_zh_tw_Gloss":"溫柔","_es_Gloss":"mansedumbre","_zh_Gloss":"温柔"}],"shortDef":"gentle, meek, the positive moral quality of dealing with people in a kind manner, with humility and consideration","mediumDef":"gentle, meek, the positive moral quality of dealing with people in a kind manner, with humility and consideration <br />also spelled <greek>πρᾶος</greek>, <b>meek, gentle, kind, forgiving,</b> <ref='Mat.5.5'>Mt. 5:5</ref>; <b>mild, benevolent, humane, humble, considerate</b> <ref='Mat.11.29; 21:5'>Mt. 11:29; 21:5</ref>; <ref='1Pe.3.4'>1Pet. 3:4</ref>*","stepGloss":"gentle","stepTransliteration":"praus","count":4,"_es_Definition":"humilde, gentil, apacible","_zh_tw_Definition":"溫和, 謙卑, 細心 (太 5:5, 21:5; 彼前 3:4)","_zh_Definition":"温和, 谦卑, 细心 (太 5:5, 21:5; 彼前 3:4)","_step_Type":"word","_stepDetailLexicalTag":"[[\"meaning\",\"G4239\",\"gentle\",4,\"πραΰς\"],[\"in the form\",\"G4235\",\"gentle\",0,\"πρᾶος\"],[\"in the form\",\"G4236\",\"gentleness\",0,\"πραότης\"]]","_vi_Definition":"nhu mì; khiêm nhu; sự dịu dàng. Học giả William Barclay viết: “Chữ πραΰς chứa đựng ý nghĩa dịu dàng, nhưng bên trong sự dịu dàng này lại có sức mạnh gang thép”","_zh_tw_Gloss":"溫柔","_es_Gloss":"manso","_zh_Gloss":"温柔"}]}